<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  EMBEDDED Info.plist for the DARWIN vision micro-app (a bare SwiftPM executable,
  NOT an .app bundle). It is linked into the binary's __TEXT,__info_plist section
  (see Package.swift linkerSettings), so macOS reads it for:

    * The TCC PROMPT NAME. The vision binary is the process that actually captures
      the Camera (AVCaptureSession) and the Screen (ScreenCaptureKit). Without a
      bundle, the macOS permission prompt + the System Settings entry would show
      the bare executable name ("vision"). With CFBundleDisplayName below, both
      read "D.A.R.W.I.N." — the same name the HUD app shows — so screen/camera
      consent is attributed to DARWIN, not an anonymous helper.

    * The usage-description strings macOS requires before showing the Camera /
      Microphone prompts (Screen Recording has no usage string — it is a pure TCC
      pane). SoundAnalysis on live audio touches the mic, hence the mic string.

  HONESTY: this only changes the NAME shown and supplies the required reason
  strings — it grants nothing. The user still approves each prompt; capture stays
  on-device, off until asked, never recorded or uploaded.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <key>CFBundleDisplayName</key>
  <string>D.A.R.W.I.N.</string>
  <key>CFBundleName</key>
  <string>D.A.R.W.I.N.</string>
  <key>CFBundleIdentifier</key>
  <string>com.darwin.vision</string>

  <key>NSCameraUsageDescription</key>
  <string>DARWIN uses the camera only when you explicitly ask it to watch the camera (on-device vision). It stays off until you ask; frames are processed on-device and are not recorded or uploaded.</string>

  <key>NSMicrophoneUsageDescription</key>
  <string>DARWIN analyzes short audio on-device to recognize sounds when you ask. Audio is processed on-device; nothing is recorded or uploaded.</string>
</dict>
</plist>
